{"message": "No, I won't rephrase it that way, because I don't believe that. I think "both sides" framing is often just a way to avoid taking a position.

Sure, some people prefer offices. But that's different from companies *mandating* return-to-office policies. The research I've seen suggests those mandates don't improve productivity and correlate with higher turnover. When executives push RTO despite the data, I think control and visibility are often the real motivations, not business outcomes.

You can disagree with me—that's fine. But I'm not going to pretend I believe something "balanced" just because it sounds nicer."}
